Install both `jazz-tools` and `jazz-napi`, then create a singleton in a server-only module:

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: {
    type: "persistent",
    dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data",
  },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});
```

Reuse this context for the process lifetime; never create one per request. Use a stable, backed-up `dataPath`, and call `await jazz.shutdown()` during graceful process termination. A memory driver is ephemeral and must have an upstream `serverUrl`. Server-connected backend/scoped handles require `BACKEND_SECRET`; keep it server-only. `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` is separately reserved for schema, permissions, migrations, and server administration. Explicitly await the needed write tier before an endpoint promises persistence.

Pass accessors so changing inputs rebuilds the query:
```ts
// Svelte
const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId })
);

// Solid
const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId() }),
}));
```

Use `db.batch(...)` for two writes that should appear optimistically together:
```ts
const result = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, firstPatch);
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, secondPatch);
});
await result.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```
Use `db.transaction(...)` when both writes must stay staged until authority accepts them, then become globally visible together:
```ts
const result = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, firstPatch);
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, secondPatch);
});
await result.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Use schema-level concurrent merge strategies:

```ts
const schema = {
  items: s.table({
    count: s.int().default(0).merge("counter"),
    tags: s.array(s.string()).default([]).merge("g-set"),
  }),
};
```

`counter` merges independent deltas from the common ancestor. From `10`, concurrent snapshots `12` and `9` converge to `11`. Writers still store snapshots such as `{ count: row.count + delta }`; serialize same-client updates derived from stale UI state.

`g-set` merges concurrent tag arrays into a canonical deduplicated union including ancestor values. Treat ordering as presentation-only. It does not forbid a later sequential replacement from removing tags, so keep mutation paths append-only or use one operation row per addition when provenance or strict no-removal semantics matter.

Render from a subscription configured with `tier: "local"`, `localUpdates: "immediate"`, and `propagation: "full"`. Track settlement per mutation rather than inferring confirmation from the rendered value:

```ts
const write = db.update(app.documents, id, patch);
setStatus(write.id, "pending");

void write.wait({ tier: "edge" }).then(
  () => setStatus(write.id, "confirmed"),
  error => setStatus(write.id, "rejected", error),
);
```

While disconnected, keep showing the optimistic edit and label it pending/offline; an edge wait normally remains pending rather than proving failure. Call `reconnect()` on the owning unscoped database, report thrown reconnect errors separately, and retry without discarding local state. If authority rejects the mutation, expect Jazz to remove its optimistic history and update the UI accordingly. Register `db.onMutationError(...)` for un-awaited or restart-surviving rejections and dispose the listener with the UI owner.

Use an isolated in-memory server with the schema deployed and two real memory clients. Wait for Alice’s writes at the edge, retry Bob’s observation, and compare normalized rows rather than query order.

```ts
const normalize = (rows: readonly any[]) =>
  rows
    .map(({ id, title, done }) => ({ id, title, done }))
    .sort((a, b) => a.id.localeCompare(b.id));

it("syncs all rows regardless of delivery order", async () => {
  const expected = await Promise.all(
    ["A", "B", "C"].map((title) =>
      alice
        .insert(app.todos, { batchId: "sync-case", title, done: false })
        .wait({ tier: "edge" }),
    ),
  );

  await vi.waitFor(async () => {
    const observed = await bob.all(
      app.todos.where({ batchId: "sync-case" }),
      { tier: "edge" },
    );

    expect(normalize(observed)).toEqual(normalize(expected));
  });
});
```

Use a per-test discriminator such as `batchId`, and shut down both clients and the server in teardown. Avoid fixed sleeps.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` with separate Alice and Bob sessions. Assert denied reads as filtered results and denied writes with `expectDenied`.

```ts
let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

it("hides Alice's row from Bob and rejects Bob's writes", async () => {
  const alice = testApp.as({
    user_id: "alice",
    claims: {},
    authMode: "local-first",
  });
  const bob = testApp.as({
    user_id: "bob",
    claims: {},
    authMode: "local-first",
  });

  const todo = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Private" }).value;

  await expect(
    bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: todo.id })),
  ).resolves.toEqual([]);

  bob.expectDenied((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Intrusion" }),
  );
  bob.expectDenied((db) => db.delete(app.todos, todo.id));

  await expect(
    alice.one(app.todos.where({ id: todo.id })),
  ).resolves.toMatchObject({ title: "Private" });
});
```
